Explore Yelp Dataset¶

Part 2: Sentiment Analysis of Yelp Reviews¶

By Yayin Cai, April 18th¶

In the previous analysis (see Explore Yelp Dataset Part 1), we analyzed the yelp dataset using PySpark and Spark SQL. Today, we would like to narrow down our analysis to a city and perform sentiment analysis on the Yelp reviews. In the analysis, we choose Pittsburgh as the study area.

1. Does Sentiment Analysis Work?¶

In this part, we'll load the data, perform a sentiment analysis, and explore the results.

1.1 Loading Datasets¶

First, we load the dataset, including the business information and the reviews.

In [4]:

In [5]:

print("There are", str(len(yelp_pittsburgh_reviews)),"reviews in Pittsburgh")
print("There are", str(len(yelp_pittsburgh_business)),"restaurants in Pittsburgh")

1.2 Simple Data Wrangling¶

1.2.1 Format the review text¶

The first step is to split the review text into its individual words and make all of the words lower-cased.

In [7]:
def split_text(string):
    string = string.lower()
    textlist = string.split()
    return textlist
In [8]:
yelp_pittsburgh_reviews["formatted_text"] = yelp_pittsburgh_reviews["text"].apply(lambda x: split_text(x))

1.2.2 Review stop words¶

Next, we want to remove any stop words from the list of words in each review.

In [10]:
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
In [11]:
stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english')) 

def remove_stop(word_list):
    filtered_list = [w for w in word_list if (not w in stop_words)]
    return filtered_list
In [12]:
yelp_pittsburgh_reviews["formatted_text"] = yelp_pittsburgh_reviews["formatted_text"].apply(lambda x: remove_stop(x))

1.3 Sentiment Analysis¶

1.3.1 Calculate polarity and subjectivity¶

Then, we can extract the subjectivity and polarity from the formatted_text.

In [14]:
from textblob import TextBlob

import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")
In [15]:
def get_sentiment(word_list):
    sentence = " ".join(word_list)
    sentiment = TextBlob(sentence).sentiment
    return pd.Series([sentiment[0], sentiment[1]])
In [16]:
yelp_pittsburgh_reviews[["polarity", "subjectivity"]] = yelp_pittsburgh_reviews["formatted_text"].apply(lambda x: get_sentiment(x))

In [18]:

From the above charts, it is obvious that polarity indicates the effectiveness of our sentiment analysis better.

1.4 The Importance of Individual Words¶

In this part, we'll explore the importance and frequency of individual words in Yelp reviews. We will identify the most common reviews and then plot the average polarity vs the user stars for the reviews where those words occur.

1.4.1 Re-format the data¶

Now, we want to reshape the dataset to extract individual words.

In [20]:
def reshape_data(review_subset):
    from pandas import Series, merge
    
    X = (review_subset['formatted_text'].apply(Series).stack().reset_index(level=1, drop=True).to_frame('word'))
    
    R = review_subset[['polarity', 'stars', 'review_id']]
    
    return merge(R, X, left_index = True, right_index = True).reset_index(drop=True)
In [21]:
yelp_pittsburgh_reviews_reshape = reshape_data(yelp_pittsburgh_reviews)

2. Correlating Restaurant Data and Household Income¶

In this part, we'll use the census API to download household income data and overlay restaurant locations.

2.1 Query the Census API¶

In this section, we will use the census_area package to download total household income by census tract (with tract geometries) from the 2017 ACS data set. We can identify the proper variable name from:

https://api.census.gov/data/2017/acs/acs5/variables.html

The FIPS codes for Pittsburgh is:

- PA code: '42'
- City code: '61000'
In [31]:
from census_area import Census

HH_income = c.acs5.state_place_tract(('NAME', 'B19013_001E'), 42, 61000, return_geometry = True)

2.3 Plot a choropleth map of the household income¶

We can plot the median household income.

In [47]:
def plotMap(geodf, figwidth, figheight, column):
    validmin = geodf[geodf[column]>=0][column].min()
    
    vmin, vmax = geodf[geodf[column]>=validmin][column].min(),geodf[column].max()

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(figwidth, figheight))
   
    geodf[geodf[column]<validmin].plot(color="#cccccc", ax=ax)
    geodf[geodf[column]>=validmin].plot(cmap = 'GnBu',column = column, linewidth=0.8, ax=ax, edgecolor='0.8')
    ax.axis('off') 
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap = 'GnBu',norm = plt.Normalize(vmin=vmin, vmax=vmax))
    sm._A = []
    cbar = fig.colorbar(sm)

from shapely.geometry import Point

def create_point(df, lon, lat):
    geometry = [Point(xy) for xy in zip(df[lon], df[lat])]
    crs = {'init': 'epsg:4326'}
    gdf = gpd.GeoDataFrame(df, crs = crs, geometry = geometry)
    return gdf

In [58]:
def plotMapCombine(basedf, geodf, figwidth, figheight, columnbase, column):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, figsize=(figwidth, figheight))
    base = basedf.plot(cmap='GnBu', ax=ax)

    [xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax] = basedf.geometry.total_bounds

    plt.xlim(xmin-0.01, xmax+0.01)
    plt.ylim(ymin-0.01, ymax+0.01)
    
    validmin = basedf[basedf[columnbase]>=0][columnbase].min()
    vmin, vmax = basedf[basedf[columnbase]>=validmin][columnbase].min(),basedf[columnbase].max()
    
    basedf[basedf[columnbase] < validmin].plot(color = "#cccccc", ax=ax)
    basedf[basedf[columnbase] >= validmin].plot(cmap = 'GnBu', column = columnbase, \
                                                linewidth = 0.8, ax = ax, edgecolor = '0.8')
 
    geodf.plot(column = column, ax = base, markersize=5, cmap = "YlOrRd", legend = True)
    
    ax.axis('off') 
    sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap = 'GnBu',norm = plt.Normalize(vmin = vmin, vmax = vmax))
    sm._A = []
    cbar = fig.colorbar(sm)
In [59]:

def plotMapTwo(basedf, geodf, figwidth, figheight, column1, column2):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2, figsize=(figwidth, figheight))
    base1 = basedf.plot(color = "white", edgecolor='grey', ax=axes[0])
    base2 = basedf.plot(color = "white", edgecolor='grey', ax=axes[1])
    
    [xmin, ymin, xmax, ymax] = basedf.geometry.total_bounds

    axes[0].set_xlim(xmin-0.01, xmax+0.01)
    axes[0].set_ylim(ymin-0.01, ymax+0.01)
    
    axes[1].set_xlim(xmin-0.01, xmax+0.01)
    axes[1].set_ylim(ymin-0.01, ymax+0.01)
    
    axes[0].set_title(column1)
    axes[1].set_title(column2)
 
    geodf.plot(column = column1, ax = base1, markersize=5, cmap = "YlOrRd", legend = True)
    geodf.plot(column = column2, ax = base2, markersize=5, cmap = "YlOrRd", legend = True)
